rbidden from watching the same scene. Audiences in Kingston and New York City exuberantly participated in the slaying of Richard III on stage, enacting the rise of the "people," and Native American leaders were enjoined to watch actors in blackface "jump Jim Crow." Dillon argues that the theater served as a "performative commons," staging debates over representation in a political world based on popular sovereignty. Her book is a capacious account of performance, aesthetics, and modernity in the eighteenth-century Atlantic world.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aTheaterxPolitical aspectszAtlantic Ocean RegionxHistoryy17th century. 0aTheaterxPolitical aspectszAtlantic Ocean RegionxHistoryy18th century. 0aTheaterxPolitical aspectszAtlantic Ocean RegionxHistoryy19th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071182040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822395737zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822395737423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822395737.jpg  a978-3-11-071182-0  DUK eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles